Performance mega patch

Post office message buffering:
Post office out boxes that are buffered with messages sent in bulk
when they exceed the buffer size. This results in a pretty significant
performance increase as it drastically reduces the number of mesasges
sent between compute nodes.

Worker graph partitions:
Currently runs the vertex programs in two seperate threads. Old
method put each vertex in its own thread (or what amounts to a
thread in dcell). This will probably need to be worked on more in the
future.

Graph distribution in threads:
Currently tries to distribute the graph by splitting it up into
1k node slices that are distributed in parallel. Each vertex
is still added to the worker individually; not in bulk.

whoops, @active = false should have been in #superstep, not #init_superstep

Improved performance (hopefully) of Worker#active?

Old version was looping through (possibly) all vertices and
mailboxes to see if the worker had any work left.

New version deals with this "dynamically" by adding an @active
member variable (set to true on initialization).

in #init_superstep, the worker will set its active state to false.
If there are any active vertices (i.e., thsoe that have not yet
voted to stop or have messages waiting), #active! will be called.

Additionally, if a message is received during a step, the postoffice will set the
worker to active by calling Worker#active!

This should ensure that after the superstep barrier is reached,
all workers that have work to do at step t + 1 will be active,
while the rest will not be active.

Attempts to improve performance with large graphs

Major stuff is in the graph loading, which now has bulk loads.

Fixed (i think) marshall dump errors

I believe that these were failing because i was inadvertantly returning
a vertex's mailbox when i did a remote push.

The problem was (I think) that a fiber could be suspended between
adding the message to the mailbox and returning the result.

Thus, the mailbox could be modified prior to the return finishing.

I.e., it could be modified before the marshall finishes.

I'm not sure if this is true, but I can't get it to fail with a 2 node
local setup anymore.
triad census appears ot be working. specs are broken

Fixed a race condition, passing specs now

There was a race condition on reading mail boxes:
One node could end up sending messages before a previous node has
read the destinations mailbox.

This is being dealt with via a separate "init_superstep" method that
reads all mailboxes prior to the "superstep" method being invoked on
workers.

This is probably not the ideal solution...

First round of architecture coding done

Not tested (at all), but, the basic architecture is coded up.

There are several major components:

1) Coordinator node. This node coordinates everything by partitioning
the graph and distributing it among worker nodes, and also serves as
a barrier between steps.

2) Worker node. This node manages the running of vertex programs for the
set of vertices assigned to it.

The worker also has several services:
A) The worker service, which is what the coordinator interacts with
B) The postoffice service, which handles delivery of vertex program
messages
C) Vertex actors. Not entirely thought through yet, but, the idea
is to have vertex programs run as actors to take advantage of multithreading
I still need to figure out what that means as far as exposing various elements
of the system to remote access.
